{"key":"processedPost-16314383","value":{"id":16314383,"first":16311676,"last":16315396,"when":1338527116,"utime":"06/01/12 08:05 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>SnozZPuPPeT said:</b><br />Should I rotate cakes that have pins growing on the opposite side of the cake to expose them to more light?<br /></blockquote><br /><br />No.&nbsp; Light anywhere on a substrate will trigger pinning anywhere else on that substrate where the conditions are right.&nbsp; Growers often find the most pins on the side opposite the light.<br /><br /><blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>SnozZPuPPeT said:</b><br />What is so wrong with having a fan in the room? What if it was a rotating fan on a timer set to get the air circulating in the room for 10 minutes every 6 hours or something along those lines? <br /></blockquote><br /><br />The fan will upset the natural air currents in the room.&nbsp; Just sit in your living room chair as the morning light comes through cracks in the curtains.&nbsp; You'll see the dust(or your exhaled smoke) swirling in all sorts of crazy patterns.&nbsp; The air in a room is never still.&nbsp; These natural air currents are what makes a shotgun terrarium function.&nbsp; Running a fan reverses the natural flow, and rather than the air entering the bottom and working up through the perlite, the air stirred around by a fan enters the holes in the growing section, screwing up the humidity.<br />RR","title":"Re: Question in regards to my operation! Experined growers please help!","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}